Data Description ¶

There are a total of 24,958 train and 2,600 test images (colored) that we have taken from microscopic images. These images are of the following categories:

Parasitized: The parasitized cells contain the Plasmodium parasite which causes malaria
Uninfected: The uninfected cells are free of the Plasmodium parasites

The files have been extracted to the local session of Google Colab. The extracted folder would have the following structure:

The extracted folder has different folders for train and test data which further contains the different sizes of images for parasitized and uninfected cells within the respective folder name.

The size of all images must be the same and should be converted to 4D arrays so that they can be used as an input for the convolutional neural network. Also, we need to create the labels for both types of images to be able to train and test the model.

Let's do the same for the training data first and then we will use the same code for the test data as well.

In [5]:
#Storing the path of the extracted "train" folder 
train_dir = '/content/cell_images/train'

#Size of image so that each image has the same size
SIZE = 64

#Empty list to store the training images after they are converted to NumPy arrays
train_images = []

#Empty list to store the training labels (0 - uninfected, 1 - parasitized)
train_labels = []
In [6]:
#We will run the same code for "parasitized" as well as "uninfected" folders within the "train" folder
for folder_name in ['/parasitized/', '/uninfected/']:
    
    #Path of the folder
    images_path = os.listdir(train_dir + folder_name)

    for i, image_name in enumerate(images_path):
        try:
            #Opening each image using the path of that image
            image = Image.open(train_dir + folder_name + image_name)

            #Resizing each image to (224,224)
            image = image.resize((SIZE, SIZE))

            #Converting images to arrays and appending that array to the empty list defined above
            train_images.append(np.array(image))

            #Creating labels for parasitized and uninfected images
            if folder_name=='/parasitized/':
                train_labels.append(1)
            else:
                train_labels.append(0)
        except Exception:
            pass       

#Converting lists to arrays
train_images = np.array(train_images)
train_labels = np.array(train_labels)

Observations and insights: as we have three colors (I assume RGB), then we have a minimum zero for each color in the train dataset, and 255 for R, 255 for G, and 240 for B. This means that all color change their intensity across full range. In the test dataset, we have a minimum 0 for each color, while the maximum is 255 for R, 239 for G, and 231 for B. Given that the maximum in each instance is 255, we also have practically a full range for each color in the test dataset as well.

Plotting the mean images for parasitized and uninfected

In [17]:
# function to find the mean
def find_mean_img(full_mat, title):
    # calculate the average
    mean_img = np.mean(full_mat, axis = 0)[0]
    # reshape it back to a matrix
    plt.imshow(mean_img)
    plt.title(f'Average {title}')
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()
    return mean_img

Converting RGB to HSV of Images using OpenCV

Converting the train data

import cv2
gfx=[]   # to hold the HSV image array
for i in np.arange(0,100,1):
  a=cv2.cvtColor(train_images[i],cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
  gfx.append(a)
gfx=np.array(gfx)

Observations and insights: typical HSV is preferred to RGB when the color is important. We already know that the coloar is critical in our case, since we are going to apply filters and search for contrast. I like HSV format in our case, because the deformations typically appear in green color, which is easier to spot relative to the rest. In RGB format, often the deformation and the rest of the cell have different intensity of red, which is not great. So I like HSV for our case.

for t,i in zip(range(5),viewimage):

Observations and insights: I Gausing blurring helping us a little bit. It looks like we preserve the contrast. The solution is going to be about applyting the filter and extract spots of the different color than the rest of the body. If the contrast is not strong enough, the cell is likely to be healthy. In the fourth image we have a large healthy white cloud, which because of Gaussian blurring becomes more similar to the rest of the cell. I think Gaussian blurring here is more appropriate the determinstic alternatives such as cropping. We might try cropping to make life easier by getting rid of the black parts on the sides, but filters should be able to find out that black pieces are not circular. ¶
